# 9front ed(1) — text editor

## Synopsis

    ed [-] [-o] [file]

## Description

ed is the standard Plan 9 text editor.  It operates on an in-memory
buffer.  Changes have no effect on the original file until a w command is
given.  If a file argument is given, ed reads it into the buffer first.

## Options

    -     Suppress printing of character counts by e, r, w commands and
          the confirming ! by ! commands.
    -o    Write all output to stderr instead of stdout (for use in pipelines).
          With no file, /fd/1 becomes the remembered file name.

## Addressing

The current line (dot, written as .) is the last line affected by a command.
Addresses are constructed as follows:

    .           current line
    $           last line of the buffer
    n           line number n (1-based)
    'x          line marked with name x (lower-case letter, set by k)
    /regexp/    search forward from . for next line matching regexp
                (wraps around to start of buffer if needed)
    ?regexp?    search backward from . (wraps around to end)
    addr+n      address plus n lines
    addr-n      address minus n lines
    addr+/re/   first line after addr matching re
    addr-/re/   first line before addr matching re
    addr+       addr + 1 (trailing + adds 1)
    addr-       addr - 1 (trailing - subtracts 1)
    +n          shorthand for .+n
    -n          shorthand for .-n
    ^           synonym for -

Addresses are separated by , (resets . between them) or ; (; sets . to
first address before evaluating second).  With no leading address before ,
or ;, line 1 is assumed; with no trailing address, $ is assumed.

## Commands

Each command takes zero, one, or two addresses.  Default addresses shown
in parentheses.

### Input/output
    (.)a        Append text after addressed line. Enter input mode; end
                with . on a line by itself. Address 0 is valid (prepend).
    (.)i        Insert text before addressed line (same as a but before).
    (.,.)c      Change: delete addressed lines, then accept new text.
    (.,.)d      Delete addressed lines.
    e filename  Edit: clear buffer, read named file, set remembered name.
    E filename  Like e but does not check for unsaved changes.
    f [filename] Print (and optionally change) the remembered file name.
    (.)r filename  Read file after addressed line. Dot left at last line read.
    (1,$)w [filename]  Write addressed lines to file. Creates if absent (mode 666).
    (1,$)W [filename]  Like w but appends to existing file.
    q           Quit. Error if buffer modified since last w/q/e.
    Q           Quit unconditionally.

### Display
    (.,.)p      Print addressed lines. Dot left at last printed line.
    (.,.)P      Synonym for p.
    (.,.)l      List in unambiguous form: tabs as \t, backspaces as \b,
                non-printing as \xXXXX. Long lines are folded.
    (.,.)n      Number: print with line numbers and tab prefix.
    (.,.)b[+-][pagesize][pln]
                Browse: print a page (default 20 lines). + or - for
                next/previous page. p/n/l selects print format.
    ($)=        Print the line number of the addressed line.

### Substitution
    (.,.)sn/regexp/replacement/
    (.,.)sn/regexp/replacement/g
    (.,.)sn/regexp/replacement   (third form implies trailing p)
        Substitute. Replace the nth match (default 1) of regexp with
        replacement on each addressed line. With g, replace all matches.
        & in replacement: matched string. \1..\9: nth subexpression.
        Literal & / \ or newline in replacement: prefix with \.
        The / delimiter may be any non-space, non-newline character.

### Move and copy
    (.,.)m a    Move addressed lines after line a.
    (.,.)t a    Transfer (copy) addressed lines after line a.
    (.,.)j      Join addressed lines into one line (remove intermediate newlines).

### Global commands
    (1,$)g/regexp/command-list   Execute command-list for every line matching regexp.
    (1,$)v/regexp/command-list   Execute command-list for every line NOT matching regexp.
        In command-list: multiple commands separated by \-continued lines.
        Trailing . for a/i/c input may be omitted on the last line.
        g and v are not permitted inside command-list.
        Any non-space non-newline character may delimit regexp.
        Bare g/regexp/ or g/regexp means g/regexp/p.

### Miscellaneous
    (.)k x      Mark addressed line with lower-case letter x.
    (.,.)u      Undo: restore the previous contents of the last substituted line.
    ! command   Run command in rc(1). Dot is unchanged.
    <newline>   An address alone is treated as a p command.
                A blank line alone is equivalent to .+1p (step through file).

## Regular expressions (Plan 9 regexp(6))

Metacharacters: . * + ? [] () | ^ $
  .       any character (not newline)
  ^       start of line
  $       end of line
  [abc]   character class; [^abc] negated (never matches newline)
  a-z     range inside []
  e*      zero or more
  e+      one or more
  e?      zero or one
  e1|e2   alternation
  (e)     grouping / subexpression (referenced by \1..\9 in s)

Backslash before a metacharacter or delimiter treats it as literal.

## Examples

Open a file and append a line after line 3:
    ed file
    3a
    new line
    .
    w

Substitute first occurrence of 'foo' with 'bar' on current line:
    s/foo/bar/

Substitute all occurrences globally across all lines:
    1,$s/foo/bar/g

Print all lines containing 'error':
    g/error/p

Delete all blank lines:
    g/^$/d

Print lines 5 through 10:
    5,10p

Move lines 3-5 to after line 10:
    3,5m10

Copy lines 1-3 to end of file:
    1,3t$

Mark current line as 'a', move elsewhere, return:
    ka
    ... (navigate) ...
    'a

Search forward for next line containing 'TODO':
    /TODO/

Non-interactive batch edit via heredoc (rc):
    ed file << '!'
    1,$s/old/new/g
    w
    q
    !

## Differences from POSIX ed

**Regexp engine:** Uses Plan 9 regexp(6), not BRE.  No POSIX character
classes ([[:alpha:]] etc.), no \n \t escape sequences in regexps (though \
before a metacharacter escapes it), no \( \) for grouping — use ( ) instead.
Alternation is | not \|.  Backreferences in regexps (\1 etc. in the pattern)
are not supported; \1..\9 work only in s replacement strings.

**b command is Browse, not BRE:** POSIX ed has no b command.  9front ed uses
b for the Browse command (paged display).  Any script that tries to use b as
a no-op or expects POSIX behavior will find Browse instead.

**P (prompt) command absent:** POSIX ed defines P to toggle a command prompt.
9front ed defines P as a synonym for p (print).  There is no prompt toggle.

**u command is limited Undo:** The u command restores only the previously
substituted line (not a general undo stack).  This is much more limited than
the full undo history some ed implementations provide.

**W (append write) command:** W wfile appends to an existing file rather than
overwriting it.  This is not in POSIX ed.

**sn/re/repl/ nth-match substitution:** The s command accepts an optional
decimal n before the delimiter to replace the nth occurrence on each line
(e.g. s2/foo/bar/ replaces the second foo).  POSIX ed does not specify this.

**; semicolon address separator:** The ; separator (which sets dot to the
first address before evaluating the second) is a 9front extension; POSIX ed
only defines , as an address separator.

**+ and - trailing address arithmetic:** Trailing + and - on addresses
(cumulative increment/decrement) and the bare - / + shorthand for .-1 / .+1
are 9front extensions.  POSIX requires the full form .+n.

**^ as synonym for -:** The ^ character as an address operator (equivalent
to -) is a compatibility extension; POSIX does not define it.

**l command escape format:** Non-printing characters are shown as \xXXXX
(backslash, x, four hex digits).  POSIX specifies a different visual
representation (octal or C-style escapes depending on implementation).

**! command uses rc(1), not sh:** Shell commands dispatched by ! are run
via /bin/rc, not /bin/sh.  Scripts using sh-specific syntax (e.g. [[, arrays,
$(( )) arithmetic) will fail.

**-o flag:** The -o flag (write all output to stderr, set remembered file to
/fd/1) is a 9front-specific option for pipeline use.  POSIX ed does not
define -o.

**File creation mode:** New files created by w are mode 666 (before umask).
POSIX leaves the mode implementation-defined.

**NUL and post-newline characters discarded:** When reading a file, ed
discards NUL bytes and all characters after the last newline.  POSIX behavior
for NUL bytes is unspecified.

**Buffer file in /tmp:** The temporary buffer file is created in /tmp as
/tmp/eXXXXX.  On hangup, unsaved work is written to ed.hup in the current
directory.

## Files

/tmp/e*     temporary buffer file
ed.hup      work is saved here on terminal hangup

